# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apache-hadoop
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The core of Apache Hadoop consists of a storage part, known as Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS), and a processing part which is a MapReduce programming model.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Hadoop splits files into large blocks and distributes them across nodes in a cluster.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] It then transfers packaged code into nodes to process the data in parallel.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] This approach takes advantage of data locality, where nodes manipulate the data they have access to.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] This allows the dataset to be processed faster and more efficiently than it would be in a more conventional supercomputer architecture that relies on a parallel file system where computation and data are distributed via high-speed networking.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Apache Hadoop's MapReduce and HDFS components were inspired by Google papers on MapReduce and Google File System.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The Hadoop framework itself is mostly written in the Java programming language, with some native code in C and command line utilities written as shell scripts.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Perl language can be easily used with Hadoop Streaming to implement the map and reduce parts of the user's program.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] According to its co-founders, Doug Cutting and Mike Cafarella, the idea of Hadoop was conceived in the Google File System paper that was published in October 2003.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The concept was extended in the Google paper *"MapReduce: Simplified Data Processing on Large Clusters".* Development started on the Apache Nutch project, but was moved to the new Hadoop subproject in January 2006.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Doug Cutting, who was working at Yahoo! at the time, named it after his son's toy elephant.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The initial code that was factored out of Nutch consisted of about 5,000 lines of code for HDFS and about 6,000 lines of code for MapReduce.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] In March 2006, Owen O'Malley was the first committer to add to the Hadoop project; Hadoop 0.1.0 was released in April 2006.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] It continues to evolve through contributions that are being made to the project.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The first design document for the Hadoop Distributed File System was written by Dhruba Borthakur in 2007.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Hadoop consists of the *Hadoop Common* package, which provides file system and operating system level abstractions, a MapReduce engine (either MapReduce/MR1 or YARN/MR2) and the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS).
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The Hadoop Common package contains the Java Archive (JAR) files and scripts needed to start Hadoop.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] For effective scheduling of work, every Hadoop-compatible file system should provide location awareness, which is the name of the rack, specifically the network switch where a worker node is.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Hadoop applications can use this information to execute code on the node where the data is, and, failing that, on the same rack/switch to reduce backbone traffic.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] HDFS uses this method when replicating data for data redundancy across multiple racks.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] This approach reduces the impact of a rack power outage or switch failure; if any of these hardware failures occurs, the data will remain available.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] A small Hadoop cluster includes a single master and multiple worker nodes.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The master node consists of a Job Tracker, Task Tracker, NameNode, and DataNode.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] A slave or *worker node* acts as both a DataNode and TaskTracker, though it is possible to have data-only and compute-only worker nodes.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] These are normally used only in nonstandard applications.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Hadoop requires the Java Runtime Environment (JRE) 1.6 or higher.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The standard startup and shutdown scripts require that Secure Shell (SSH) be set up between nodes in the cluster.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] In a larger cluster, HDFS nodes are managed through a dedicated NameNode server to host the file system index, and a secondary NameNode that can generate snapshots of the namenode's memory structures, thereby preventing file-system corruption and loss of data.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Similarly, a standalone JobTracker server can manage job scheduling across nodes.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] When Hadoop MapReduce is used with an alternate file system, the NameNode, secondary NameNode, and DataNode architecture of HDFS are replaced by the file-system-specific equivalents.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The *Hadoop distributed file system* (HDFS) is a distributed, scalable, and portable file system written in Java for the Hadoop framework.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] A Hadoop instance is divided into HDFS and MapReduce.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] HDFS is used for storing the data and MapReduce is used for processing data.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Top three are Master Services/Daemons/Nodes and bottom two are Slave Services.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Master Services can communicate with each other and in the same way Slave services can communicate with each other.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Name Node is a master node and Data node is its corresponding Slave node and can talk with each other.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Hadoop cluster has nominally a single namenode plus a cluster of datanodes, although redundancy options are available for the namenode due to its criticality.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Each datanode serves up blocks of data over the network using a block protocol specific to HDFS.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The file system uses TCP/IP sockets for communication.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Clients use remote procedure calls (RPC) to communicate with each other.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] HDFS stores large files (typically in the range of gigabytes to terabytes) across multiple machines.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] It achieves reliability by replicating the data across multiple hosts, and hence theoretically does not require redundant array of independent disks (RAID) storage on hosts (but to increase input-output (I/O) performance some RAID configurations are still useful).
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] With the default replication value, 3, data is stored on three nodes: two on the same rack, and one on a different rack.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Data nodes can talk to each other to rebalance data, to move copies around, and to keep the replication of data high.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] HDFS is not fully POSIX-compliant, because the requirements for a POSIX file-system differ from the target goals of a Hadoop application.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The trade-off of not having a fully POSIX-compliant file-system is increased performance for data throughput and support for non-POSIX operations such as Append.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] In May 2012, high-availability capabilities were added to HDFS, letting the main metadata server called the NameNode manually fail-over onto a backup.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The project has also started developing automatic fail-overs.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The HDFS file system includes a so-called *secondary namenode*, a misleading term that some might incorrectly interpret as a backup namenode when the primary namenode goes offline.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] In fact, the secondary namenode regularly connects with the primary namenode and builds snapshots of the primary namenode's directory information, which the system then saves to local or remote directories.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] These checkpointed images can be used to restart a failed primary namenode without having to replay the entire journal of file-system actions, then to edit the log to create an up-to-date directory structure.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Because the namenode is the single point for storage and management of metadata, it can become a bottleneck for supporting a huge number of files, especially a large number of small files.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] HDFS Federation, a new addition, aims to tackle this problem to a certain extent by allowing multiple namespaces served by separate namenodes.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Moreover, there are some issues in HDFS such as small file issues, scalability problems, Single Point of Failure (SPoF), and bottlenecks in huge metadata requests.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] One advantage of using HDFS is data awareness between the job tracker and task tracker.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The job tracker schedules map or reduce jobs to task trackers with an awareness of the data location.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] For example: if node A contains data (a, b, c) and node X contains data (x, y, z), the job tracker schedules node A to perform map or reduce tasks on (a, b, c) and node X would be scheduled to perform map or reduce tasks on (x, y, z).
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] This reduces the amount of traffic that goes over the network and prevents unnecessary data transfer.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] When Hadoop is used with other file systems, this advantage is not always available.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] This can have a significant impact on job-completion times as demonstrated with data-intensive jobs.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] HDFS was designed for mostly immutable files and may not be suitable for systems requiring concurrent write operations.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] HDFS can be mounted directly with a Filesystem in Userspace (FUSE) virtual file system on Linux and some other Unix systems.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] File access can be achieved through the native Java API, the Thrift API (generates a client in a number of languages e.g.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] C++, Java, Python, PHP, Ruby, Erlang, Perl, Haskell, C#, Cocoa, Smalltalk, and OCaml), the command-line interface, the HDFS-UI web application over HTTP, or via 3rd-party network client libraries.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] HDFS is designed for portability across various hardware platforms and for compatibility with a variety of underlying operating systems.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The HDFS design introduces portability limitations that result in some performance bottlenecks, since the Java implementation cannot use features that are exclusive to the platform on which HDFS is running.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Due to its widespread integration into enterprise-level infrastructure, monitoring HDFS performance at scale has become an increasingly important issue.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Monitoring end-to-end performance requires tracking metrics from datanodes, namenodes, and the underlying operating system.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] There are currently several monitoring platforms to track HDFS performance, including Hortonworks, Cloudera, and Datadog.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Hadoop works directly with any distributed file system that can be mounted by the underlying operating system by simply using a `file://` URL; however, this comes at a price – the loss of locality.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] To reduce network traffic, Hadoop needs to know which servers are closest to the data, information that Hadoop-specific file system bridges can provide.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] A number of third-party file system bridges have also been written, none of which are currently in Hadoop distributions.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] However, some commercial distributions of Hadoop ship with an alternative file system as the default – specifically IBM and MapR.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Atop the file systems comes the MapReduce Engine, which consists of one *JobTracker*, to which client applications submit MapReduce jobs.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The JobTracker pushes work to available *TaskTracker* nodes in the cluster, striving to keep the work as close to the data as possible.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] With a rack-aware file system, the JobTracker knows which node contains the data, and which other machines are nearby.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] If the work cannot be hosted on the actual node where the data resides, priority is given to nodes in the same rack.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] This reduces network traffic on the main backbone network.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] If a TaskTracker fails or times out, that part of the job is rescheduled.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The TaskTracker on each node spawns a separate Java virtual machine (JVM) process to prevent the TaskTracker itself from failing if the running job crashes its JVM.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] A heartbeat is sent from the TaskTracker to the JobTracker every few minutes to check its status.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The Job Tracker and TaskTracker status and information is exposed by Jetty and can be viewed from a web browser.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] If one TaskTracker is very slow, it can delay the entire MapReduce job – especially towards the end, when everything can end up waiting for the slowest task.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] With speculative execution enabled, however, a single task can be executed on multiple slave nodes.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] By default Hadoop uses FIFO scheduling, and optionally 5 scheduling priorities to schedule jobs from a work queue.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] In version 0.19 the job scheduler was refactored out of the JobTracker, while adding the ability to use an alternate scheduler (such as the *Fair scheduler* or the *Capacity scheduler*, described next).
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The fair scheduler was developed by Facebook.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The goal of the fair scheduler is to provide fast response times for small jobs and quality of service (QoS) for production jobs.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The fair scheduler has three basic concepts.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Each pool is assigned a guaranteed minimum share.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] By default, jobs that are uncategorized go into a default pool.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Pools have to specify the minimum number of map slots, reduce slots, as well as a limit on the number of running jobs.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The capacity scheduler was developed by Yahoo.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The capacity scheduler supports several features that are similar to those of the fair scheduler.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Free resources are allocated to queues beyond their total capacity.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Within a queue, a job with a high level of priority has access to the queue's resources.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] There is no preemption once a job is running.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The biggest difference between Hadoop 1 and Hadoop 2 is the addition of YARN (Yet Another Resource Negotiator), which replaced the MapReduce engine in the first version of Hadoop.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] YARN strives to allocate resources to various applications effectively.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] It runs two daemons, which take care of two different tasks: the *resource manager*, which does job tracking and resource allocation to applications, the *application master*, which monitors progress of the execution.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] There are important features provided by Hadoop 3.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] For example, while there is one single *namenode* in Hadoop 2, Hadoop 3, enables having multiple name nodes, which solves the single point of failure problem.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] In Hadoop 3, there are containers working in principle of Docker, which reduces time spent on application development.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] One of the biggest changes is that Hadoop 3 decreases storage overhead with erasure coding.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Also, Hadoop 3 permits usage of GPU hardware within the cluster, which is a very substantial benefit to execute deep learning algorithms on a Hadoop cluster.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The HDFS is not restricted to MapReduce jobs.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] It can be used for other applications, many of which are under development at Apache.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] The list includes the HBase database, the Apache Mahout machine learning system, and the Apache Hive data warehouse.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Theoretically, Hadoop could be used for any workload that is batch-oriented rather than real-time, is very data-intensive, and benefits from parallel processing.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] It can also be used to complement a real-time system, such as lambda architecture, Apache Storm, Flink, and Spark Streaming.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Inc. launched what they claimed was the world's largest Hadoop production application.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Search Webmap is a Hadoop application that runs on a Linux cluster with more than 10,000 cores and produced data that was used in every Yahoo! web search query.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] There are multiple Hadoop clusters at Yahoo! and no HDFS file systems or MapReduce jobs are split across multiple data centers.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Every Hadoop cluster node bootstraps the Linux image, including the Hadoop distribution.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Work that the clusters perform is known to include the index calculations for the Yahoo! search engine.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] In June 2009, Yahoo! made the source code of its Hadoop version available to the open-source community.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] In 2010, Facebook claimed that they had the largest Hadoop cluster in the world with 21 PB of storage.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] In June 2012, they announced the data had grown to 100 PB and later that year they announced that the data was growing by roughly half a PB per day.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] As of 2013, Hadoop adoption had become widespread: more than half of the Fortune 50 companies used Hadoop.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] Influential papers on the birth, growth, and curation of Hadoop and big data processing include: Jeffrey Dean, Sanjay Ghemawat (2004) MapReduce: Simplified Data Processing on Large Clusters, Google.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] This paper inspired Doug Cutting to develop an open-source implementation of the Map-Reduce framework.
[src:apache-hadoop/apache-hadoop] He named it Hadoop, after his son's toy elephant.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] A **clustered file system** (**CFS**) is a file system which is shared by being simultaneously mounted on multiple servers.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] There are several approaches to clustering, most of which do not employ a clustered file system (only direct attached storage for each node).
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] Clustered file systems can provide features like location-independent addressing and redundancy which improve reliability or reduce the complexity of the other parts of the cluster.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] **Parallel file systems** are a type of clustered file system that spread data across multiple storage nodes, usually for redundancy or performance.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] A **shared-disk file system** uses a storage area network (SAN) to allow multiple computers to gain direct disk access at the block level.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] Access control and translation from file-level operations that applications use to block-level operations used by the SAN must take place on the client node.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] Shared-disk file-systems commonly employ some sort of fencing mechanism to prevent data corruption in case of node failures, because an unfenced device can cause data corruption if it loses communication with its sister nodes and tries to access the same information other nodes are accessing.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] The underlying storage area network may use any of a number of block-level protocols, including SCSI, iSCSI, HyperSCSI, ATA over Ethernet (AoE), Fibre Channel, network block device, and InfiniBand.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] There are different architectural approaches to a shared-disk filesystem.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] Some distribute file information across all the servers in a cluster (fully distributed).
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] Distributed data stores, by contrast, require using a different API or library and have different semantics (most often those of a database).
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] Distributed file systems may aim for "transparency" in a number of aspects.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] That is, they aim to be "invisible" to client programs, which "see" a system which is similar to a local file system.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] Behind the scenes, the distributed file system handles locating files, transporting data, and potentially providing other features listed below.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] The Incompatible Timesharing System used virtual devices for transparent inter-machine file system access in the 1960s.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] More file servers were developed in the 1970s.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] In 1976, Digital Equipment Corporation created the File Access Listener (FAL), an implementation of the Data Access Protocol as part of DECnet Phase II which became the first widely used network file system.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] In 1984, Sun Microsystems created the file system called "Network File System" (NFS) which became the first widely used Internet Protocol based network file system.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] Other notable network file systems are Andrew File System (AFS), Apple Filing Protocol (AFP), NetWare Core Protocol (NCP), and Server Message Block (SMB) which is also known as Common Internet File System (CIFS).
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] In 1986, IBM announced client and server support for Distributed Data Management Architecture (DDM) for the System/36, System/38, and IBM mainframe computers running CICS.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] This was followed by the support for IBM Personal Computer, AS/400, IBM mainframe computers under the MVS and VSE operating systems, and FlexOS.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] DDM also became the foundation for Distributed Relational Database Architecture, also known as DRDA.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] There are many peer-to-peer network protocols for open-source distributed file systems for cloud or closed-source clustered file systems, e. g.: 9P, AFS, Coda, CIFS/SMB, DCE/DFS, WekaFS, Lustre, PanFS, Google File System, Mnet, Chord Project.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] Network-attached storage (NAS) provides both storage and a file system, like a shared disk file system on top of a storage area network (SAN).
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] The failure of disk hardware or a given storage node in a cluster can create a single point of failure that can result in data loss or unavailability.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] Fault tolerance and high availability can be provided through data replication of one sort or another, so that data remains intact and available despite the failure of any single piece of equipment.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] For examples, see the lists of distributed fault-tolerant file systems and distributed parallel fault-tolerant file systems.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] A common performance measurement of a clustered file system is the amount of time needed to satisfy service requests.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] In conventional systems, this time consists of a disk-access time and a small amount of CPU-processing time.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] But in a clustered file system, a remote access has additional overhead due to the distributed structure.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] This includes the time to deliver the request to a server, the time to deliver the response to the client, and for each direction, a CPU overhead of running the communication protocol software.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] Concurrency control becomes an issue when more than one person or client is accessing the same file or block and want to update it.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] Hence updates to the file from one client should not interfere with access and updates from other clients.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] This problem is more complex with file systems due to concurrent overlapping writes, where different writers write to overlapping regions of the file concurrently.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] This problem is usually handled by concurrency control or locking which may either be built into the file system or provided by an add-on protocol.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] IBM mainframes in the 1970s could share physical disks and file systems if each machine had its own channel connection to the drives' control units.
[src:apache-hadoop/clustered-file-system] In the 1980s, Digital Equipment Corporation's TOPS-20 and OpenVMS clusters (VAX/ALPHA/IA64) included shared disk file systems.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] The components of a distributed system communicate and coordinate their actions by passing messages to one another in order to achieve a common goal.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Three challenges of distributed systems are: maintaining concurrency of components, overcoming the lack of a global clock, and managing the independent failure of components.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] When a component of one system fails, the entire system does not fail.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Examples of distributed systems vary from SOA-based systems to microservices to massively multiplayer online games to peer-to-peer applications.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Distributed systems cost more than monolithic architectures, primarily due to increased needs for additional hardware, servers, gateways, firewalls, new subnets, proxies, and so on.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Distributed systems can also suffer from fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Conversely, a well-designed distributed system is more scalable, more durable, more changeable, and more fine-tuned than a monolithic application deployed on a single machine.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] According to Marc Brooker: "a system is scalable in the range where marginal cost of additional workload is nearly constant." Serverless technologies fit this definition but the total cost of ownership, and not just the infrastructure cost must be considered.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] A computer program that runs within a distributed system is called a **distributed program**, and *distributed programming* is the process of writing such programs.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] There are many types of implementations for the message-passing mechanism, including pure HTTP, RPC-like connectors, and message queues.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] The word *distributed* in terms such as "distributed system", "distributed programming", and "distributed algorithm" originally referred to computer networks where individual computers were physically distributed within some geographical area.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] The terms are nowadays used in a much wider sense, even referring to autonomous processes that run on the same physical computer and interact with each other by message passing.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] A distributed system may have a common goal, such as solving a large computational problem; the user then perceives the collection of autonomous processors as a unit.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Alternatively, each computer may have its own user with individual needs, and the purpose of the distributed system is to coordinate the use of shared resources or provide communication services to the users.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] In distributed systems, events represent a fact or state change (e.g., *OrderPlaced*) and are typically broadcast asynchronously to multiple consumers, promoting loose coupling and scalability.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] While events generally don't expect an immediate response, acknowledgment mechanisms are often implemented at the infrastructure level (e.g., Kafka commit offsets, SNS delivery statuses) rather than being an inherent part of the event pattern itself.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] In contrast, messages serve a broader role, encompassing commands (e.g., *ProcessPayment*), events (e.g., *PaymentProcessed*), and documents (e.g., *DataPayload*).
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Both events and messages can support various delivery guarantees, including at-least-once, at-most-once, and exactly-once, depending on the technology stack and implementation.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] However, exactly-once delivery is often achieved through idempotency mechanisms rather than true, infrastructure-level exactly-once semantics.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Delivery patterns for both events and messages include publish/subscribe (one-to-many) and point-to-point (one-to-one).
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] While request/reply is technically possible, it is more commonly associated with messaging patterns rather than pure event-driven systems.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Events excel at state propagation and decoupled notifications, while messages are better suited for command execution, workflow orchestration, and explicit coordination.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Modern architectures commonly combine both approaches, leveraging events for distributed state change notifications and messages for targeted command execution and structured workflows based on specific timing, ordering, and delivery requirements.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Distributed systems are groups of networked computers which share a common goal for their work.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have much overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Parallel computing may be seen as a particularly tightly coupled form of distributed computing, and distributed computing may be seen as a loosely coupled form of parallel computing.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] The figure on the right illustrates the difference between distributed and parallel systems.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Figure (a) is a schematic view of a typical distributed system; the system is represented as a network topology in which each node is a computer and each line connecting the nodes is a communication link.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Figure (b) shows the same distributed system in more detail: each computer has its own local memory, and information can be exchanged only by passing messages from one node to another by using the available communication links.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Figure (c) shows a parallel system in which each processor has a direct access to a shared memory.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] The situation is further complicated by the traditional uses of the terms parallel and distributed *algorithm* that do not quite match the above definitions of parallel and distributed *systems* (see below for more detailed discussion).
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Nevertheless, as a rule of thumb, high-performance parallel computation in a shared-memory multiprocessor uses parallel algorithms while the coordination of a large-scale distributed system uses distributed algorithms.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] The use of concurrent processes which communicate through message-passing has its roots in operating system architectures studied in the 1960s.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] The first widespread distributed systems were local-area networks such as Ethernet, which was invented in the 1970s.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] ARPANET, one of the predecessors of the Internet, was introduced in the late 1960s, and ARPANET e-mail was invented in the early 1970s.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] E-mail became the most successful application of ARPANET, and it is probably the earliest example of a large-scale distributed application.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] In addition to ARPANET (and its successor, the global Internet), other early worldwide computer networks included Usenet and FidoNet from the 1980s, both of which were used to support distributed discussion systems.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] The study of distributed computing became its own branch of computer science in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] The first conference in the field, Symposium on Principles of Distributed Computing (PODC), dates back to 1982, and its counterpart International Symposium on Distributed Computing (DISC) was first held in Ottawa in 1985 as the International Workshop on Distributed Algorithms on Graphs.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Various hardware and software architectures are used for distributed computing.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] At a lower level, it is necessary to interconnect multiple CPUs with some sort of network, regardless of whether that network is printed onto a circuit board or made up of loosely coupled devices and cables.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] At a higher level, it is necessary to interconnect processes running on those CPUs with some sort of communication system.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Distributed programming typically falls into one of several basic architectures: client–server, three-tier, *n*-tier, or peer-to-peer; or categories: loose coupling, or tight coupling.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Another basic aspect of distributed computing architecture is the method of communicating and coordinating work among concurrent processes.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Through various message passing protocols, processes may communicate directly with one another, typically in a main/sub relationship.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Alternatively, a "database-centric" architecture can enable distributed computing to be done without any form of direct inter-process communication, by utilizing a shared database.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Database-centric architecture in particular provides relational processing analytics in a schematic architecture allowing for live environment relay.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] This enables distributed computing functions both within and beyond the parameters of a networked database.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing approach in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Each cell operates independently, processing requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] A cell typically consists of multiple services or application components and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Some implementations replicate entire sets of services across multiple cells, while others partition workloads between cells.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] In replicated models, requests may be rerouted to an operational cell if another experiences a failure.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] This design is intended to enhance system resilience by reducing the impact of localized failures.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Some implementations employ circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to prevent cascading failures among services, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in some large-scale distributed systems, particularly in cloud-native and high-availability environments, where fault isolation and redundancy are key design considerations.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Its implementation varies depending on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and operational objectives.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] According to Reactive Manifesto, reactive distributed systems are responsive, resilient, elastic and message-driven.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Subsequently, Reactive systems are more flexible, loosely-coupled and scalable.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] To make your systems reactive, you are advised to implement Reactive Principles.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Reactive Principles are a set of principles and patterns which help to make your cloud native application as well as edge native applications more reactive.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Many tasks that we would like to automate by using a computer are of question–answer type: we would like to ask a question and the computer should produce an answer.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] In theoretical computer science, such tasks are called computational problems.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Formally, a computational problem consists of *instances* together with a *solution* for each instance.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Instances are questions that we can ask, and solutions are desired answers to these questions.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Theoretical computer science seeks to understand which computational problems can be solved by using a computer (computability theory) and how efficiently (computational complexity theory).
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Traditionally, it is said that a problem can be solved by using a computer if we can design an algorithm that produces a correct solution for any given instance.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Such an algorithm can be implemented as a computer program that runs on a general-purpose computer: the program reads a problem instance from input, performs some computation, and produces the solution as output.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Formalisms such as random-access machines or universal Turing machines can be used as abstract models of a sequential general-purpose computer executing such an algorithm.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] The field of concurrent and distributed computing studies similar questions in the case of either multiple computers, or a computer that executes a network of interacting processes: which computational problems can be solved in such a network and how efficiently?
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] However, it is not at all obvious what is meant by "solving a problem" in the case of a concurrent or distributed system: for example, what is the task of the algorithm designer, and what is the concurrent or distributed equivalent of a sequential general-purpose computer?
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] The discussion below focuses on the case of multiple computers, although many of the issues are the same for concurrent processes running on a single computer.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] In the case of distributed algorithms, computational problems are typically related to graphs.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Often the graph that describes the structure of the computer network *is* the problem instance.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] This is illustrated in the following example.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Consider the computational problem of finding a coloring of a given graph *G*.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] While the field of parallel algorithms has a different focus than the field of distributed algorithms, there is much interaction between the two fields.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] For example, the Cole–Vishkin algorithm for graph coloring was originally presented as a parallel algorithm, but the same technique can also be used directly as a distributed algorithm.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Moreover, a parallel algorithm can be implemented either in a parallel system (using shared memory) or in a distributed system (using message passing).
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] The traditional boundary between parallel and distributed algorithms (choose a suitable network vs. run in any given network) does not lie in the same place as the boundary between parallel and distributed systems (shared memory vs. message passing).
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] In parallel algorithms, yet another resource in addition to time and space is the number of computers.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Indeed, often there is a trade-off between the running time and the number of computers: the problem can be solved faster if there are more computers running in parallel (see speedup).
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] If a decision problem can be solved in polylogarithmic time by using a polynomial number of processors, then the problem is said to be in the class NC.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] The class NC can be defined equally well by using the PRAM formalism or Boolean circuits—PRAM machines can simulate Boolean circuits efficiently and vice versa.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] In the analysis of distributed algorithms, more attention is usually paid on communication operations than computational steps.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Perhaps the simplest model of distributed computing is a synchronous system where all nodes operate in a lockstep fashion.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] This model is commonly known as the LOCAL model.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] During each *communication round*, all nodes in parallel (1) receive the latest messages from their neighbours, (2) perform arbitrary local computation, and (3) send new messages to their neighbors.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] In such systems, a central complexity measure is the number of synchronous communication rounds required to complete the task.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] This complexity measure is closely related to the diameter of the network.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] On the one hand, any computable problem can be solved trivially in a synchronous distributed system in approximately 2*D* communication rounds: simply gather all information in one location (*D* rounds), solve the problem, and inform each node about the solution (*D* rounds).
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] On the other hand, if the running time of the algorithm is much smaller than *D* communication rounds, then the nodes in the network must produce their output without having the possibility to obtain information about distant parts of the network.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] In other words, the nodes must make globally consistent decisions based on information that is available in their *local D-neighbourhood*.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Many distributed algorithms are known with the running time much smaller than *D* rounds, and understanding which problems can be solved by such algorithms is one of the central research questions of the field.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Typically an algorithm which solves a problem in polylogarithmic time in the network size is considered efficient in this model.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Another commonly used measure is the total number of bits transmitted in the network (cf. communication complexity).
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] The features of this concept are typically captured with the CONGEST(B) model, which is similarly defined as the LOCAL model, but where single messages can only contain B bits.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Traditional computational problems take the perspective that the user asks a question, a computer (or a distributed system) processes the question, then produces an answer and stops.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] However, there are also problems where the system is required not to stop, including the dining philosophers problem and other similar mutual exclusion problems.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] In these problems, the distributed system is supposed to continuously coordinate the use of shared resources so that no conflicts or deadlocks occur.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] There are also fundamental challenges that are unique to distributed computing, for example those related to *fault-tolerance*.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Examples of related problems include consensus problems, Byzantine fault tolerance, and self-stabilisation.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Note that in distributed systems, latency should be measured through "99th percentile" because "median" and "average" can be misleading.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] The network nodes communicate among themselves in order to decide which of them will get into the "coordinator" state.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] For that, they need some method in order to break the symmetry among them.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] For example, if each node has unique and comparable identities, then the nodes can compare their identities, and decide that the node with the highest identity is the coordinator.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] The definition of this problem is often attributed to LeLann, who formalized it as a method to create a new token in a token ring network in which the token has been lost.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Coordinator election algorithms are designed to be economical in terms of total bytes transmitted, and time.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] The algorithm suggested by Gallager, Humblet, and Spira for general undirected graphs has had a strong impact on the design of distributed algorithms in general, and won the Dijkstra Prize for an influential paper in distributed computing.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Many other algorithms were suggested for different kinds of network graphs, such as undirected rings, unidirectional rings, complete graphs, grids, directed Euler graphs, and others.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] A general method that decouples the issue of the graph family from the design of the coordinator election algorithm was suggested by Korach, Kutten, and Moran.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] In order to perform coordination, distributed systems employ the concept of coordinators.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] The coordinator election problem is to choose a process from among a group of processes on different processors in a distributed system to act as the central coordinator.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] Several central coordinator election algorithms exist.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] So far the focus has been on *designing* a distributed system that solves a given problem.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] A complementary research problem is *studying* the properties of a given distributed system.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] The halting problem is an analogous example from the field of centralised computation: we are given a computer program and the task is to decide whether it halts or runs forever.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] The halting problem is undecidable in the general case, and naturally understanding the behaviour of a computer network is at least as hard as understanding the behaviour of one computer.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] However, there are many interesting special cases that are decidable.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] In particular, it is possible to reason about the behaviour of a network of finite-state machines.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] One example is telling whether a given network of interacting (asynchronous and non-deterministic) finite-state machines can reach a deadlock.
[src:apache-hadoop/distributed-computing] This problem is PSPACE-complete, i.e., it is decidable, but not likely that there is an efficient (centralised, parallel or distributed) algorithm that solves the problem in the case of large networks.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance specifically refers to a system's capability to handle faults without any degradation or downtime.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] In the event of an error, end-users remain unaware of any issues.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Conversely, a system that experiences errors with some interruption in service or graceful degradation of performance is termed 'resilient'.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] In resilience, the system adapts to the error, maintaining service but acknowledging a certain impact on performance.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Typically, fault tolerance describes computer systems, ensuring the overall system remains functional despite hardware or software issues.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Non-computing examples include structures that retain their integrity despite damage from fatigue, corrosion or impact.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] The first known fault-tolerant computer was SAPO, built in 1951 in Czechoslovakia by Antonín Svoboda.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Its basic design was magnetic drums connected via relays, with a voting method of memory error detection (triple modular redundancy).
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Several other machines were developed along this line, mostly for military use.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Computers with a high amount of runtime that would be under heavy use, such as many of the supercomputers used by insurance companies for their probability monitoring.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Most of the development in the so-called LLNM (Long Life, No Maintenance) computing was done by NASA during the 1960s, in preparation for Project Apollo and other research aspects.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] NASA's first machine went into a space observatory, and their second attempt, the JSTAR computer, was used in Voyager.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] This computer had a backup of memory arrays to use memory recovery methods and thus it was called the Jet Propulsion Laboratory Self-Testing-And-Repairing computer.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] It could detect its own errors and fix them or use redundant modules as needed.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] The computer is still working, as of early 2022.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Hyper-dependable computers were pioneered mostly by aircraft manufacturers, nuclear power companies, and the railroad industry in the United States.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] These entities needed computers with massive amounts of uptime that would fail gracefully enough during a fault to allow continued operation, while relying on constant human monitoring of computer output to detect faults.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] IBM developed the first computer of this kind for NASA for guidance of Saturn V rockets.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Later, BNSF, Unisys, and General Electric built their own.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] In the 1970s, much work happened in the field.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] For instance, F14 CADC had built-in self-test and redundancy.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] In general, the early efforts at fault-tolerant designs were focused mainly on internal diagnosis, where a fault would indicate something was failing and a worker could replace it.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] SAPO, for instance, had a method by which faulty memory drums would emit a noise before failure.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Later efforts showed that to be fully effective, the system had to be self-repairing and diagnosing – isolating a fault and then implementing a redundant backup while alerting a need for repair.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] This is known as N-model redundancy, where faults cause automatic fail-safes and a warning to the operator, and it is still the most common form of level one fault-tolerant design in use today.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Voting was another initial method, as discussed above, with multiple redundant backups operating constantly and checking each other's results.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] For example, if four components reported an answer of 5 and one component reported an answer of 6, the other four would "vote" that the fifth component was faulty and have it taken out of service.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] This is called M out of N majority voting.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Historically, the trend has been to move away from N-model and toward M out of N, as the complexity of systems and the difficulty of ensuring the transitive state from fault-negative to fault-positive did not disrupt operations.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Tandem Computers, in 1976 and Stratus Technologies were among the first companies specializing in the design of fault-tolerant computer systems for online transaction processing.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Hardware fault tolerance sometimes requires that broken parts be removed and replaced with new parts while the system is still operational (in computing known as *hot swapping*).
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Such a system implemented with a single backup is known as **single point tolerant** and represents the vast majority of fault-tolerant systems.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] In such systems the mean time between failures should be long enough for the operators to have sufficient time to fix the broken devices (mean time to repair) before the backup also fails.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] It is helpful if the time between failures is as long as possible, but this is not specifically required in a fault-tolerant system.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance is notably successful in computer applications.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Tandem Computers built their entire business on such machines, which used single-point tolerance to create their NonStop systems with uptimes measured in years.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Fail-safe architectures may encompass also the computer software, for example by process replication.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Data formats may also be designed to degrade gracefully.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Hyper Text Markup Language (HTML) for example, is designed to be forward compatible, allowing Web browsers to ignore new and unsupported HTML entities without causing the document to be unusable.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Additionally, proper user interface design mandates that websites provide an optional lightweight front end that does not rely on JavaScript and has a minimal layout, to ensure wide accessibility and outreach.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] A highly fault-tolerant system might continue at the same level of performance even though one or more components have failed.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] For example, a building with a backup electrical generator will provide the same voltage to wall outlets even if the grid power fails.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] A system that is designed to fail safe, or fail-secure, or **fail gracefully**, whether it functions at a reduced level or fails completely, does so in a way that protects people, property, or data from injury, damage, intrusion, or disclosure.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] In computers, a program might fail-safe by executing a graceful exit (as opposed to an uncontrolled crash) to prevent data corruption after an error occurs.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] A similar distinction is made between "failing well" and "failing badly".
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] A system designed to experience **graceful degradation**, or to **fail soft** (used in computing, similar to "fail safe") operates at a reduced level of performance after some component fails.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] For example, if grid power fails, a building may operate lighting at reduced levels or elevators at reduced speeds.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] In computing, if insufficient network bandwidth is available to stream an online video, a lower-resolution version might be streamed in place of the high-resolution version.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Progressive enhancement is another example, where web pages are available in a basic functional format for older, small-screen, or limited-capability web browsers, but in an enhanced version for browsers capable of handling additional technologies or that have a larger display.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] In fault-tolerant computer systems, programs that are considered robust are designed to continue operation despite an error, exception, or invalid input, instead of failing completely.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Software brittleness is the opposite of robustness.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Resilient networks continue to transmit data despite the failure of some links or nodes.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Resilient buildings and infrastructure are likewise expected to prevent complete failure in situations like earthquakes, floods, or collisions.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] A system with high failure transparency will alert users that a component failure has occurred, even if it continues to operate with full performance, so that failure can be repaired or imminent complete failure anticipated.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Likewise, a fail-fast component is designed to report at the first point of failure, rather than generating reports when downstream components fail.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] This allows easier diagnosis of the underlying problem, and may prevent improper operation in a broken state.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] A **single fault condition** is a situation where one means for protection against a hazard is defective.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] If a single fault condition results unavoidably in another single fault condition, the two failures are considered one single fault condition.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Providing fault-tolerant design for every component is normally not an option.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Associated redundancy brings a number of penalties: increase in weight, size, power consumption, cost, as well as time to design, verify, and test.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] An example of a component that passes all the tests is a car's occupant restraint system.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] While the *primary* occupant restraint system is not normally thought of, it is gravity.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] If the vehicle rolls over or undergoes severe g-forces, then this primary method of occupant restraint may fail.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Restraining the occupants during such an accident is absolutely critical to safety, so the first test is passed.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Accidents causing occupant ejection were quite common before seat belts, so the second test is passed.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] The cost of a redundant restraint method like seat belts is quite low, both economically and in terms of weight and space, so the third test is passed.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Therefore, adding seat belts to all vehicles is an excellent idea.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Other "supplemental restraint systems", such as airbags, are more expensive and so pass that test by a smaller margin.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] It would also be prohibitively costly to further double-up the main components and they would add considerable weight.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] However, the similarly critical systems for actuating the brakes under driver control are inherently less robust, generally using a cable (which can rust, stretch, jam, or snap) or hydraulic fluid (which can leak, boil and develop bubbles, or absorb water and thus lose effectiveness).
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] The cumulatively unlikely combination of total foot brake failure with the need for harsh braking in an emergency will likely result in a collision, but still one at lower speed than would otherwise have been the case.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] In comparison with the foot pedal activated service brake, the parking brake itself is a less critical item, and unless it is being used as a one-time backup for the footbrake, will not cause immediate danger if it is found to be nonfunctional at the moment of application.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, on shallow gradients, the transmission can be shifted into Park, Reverse or First gear, and the transmission lock / engine compression used to hold it stationary, as there is no need for them to include the sophistication to first bring the vehicle to a halt.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] On motorcycles, a similar level of fail-safety is provided by simpler methods; first, the front and rear brake systems are entirely separate, regardless of their method of activation (that can be cable, rod or hydraulic), allowing one system to fail entirely while leaving the other unaffected.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Fault isolation to the failing component – When a failure occurs, the system must be able to isolate the failure to the offending component.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] This requires the addition of dedicated failure detection mechanisms that exist only for the purpose of fault isolation.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Recovery from a fault condition requires classifying the fault or failing component.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Faults are commonly categorized by their locality (internal or external to the system), cause (natural or human-made), duration (permanent or transient), and effect on system behavior.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Fault containment to prevent propagation of the failure – Some failure mechanisms can cause a system to fail by propagating the failure to the rest of the system.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] An example of this kind of failure is the "rogue transmitter" that can swamp legitimate communication in a system and cause overall system failure.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Firewalls or other mechanisms that isolate a rogue transmitter or failing component to protect the system are required.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Availability of reversion modes, which is the abandonment of recent changes, usually to software, that bring a system back to reasonably proper behavior and function.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] In addition, fault-tolerant systems are characterized in terms of both planned service outages and unplanned service outages.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] These are usually measured at the application level and not just at a hardware level.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] The figure of merit is called availability and is expressed as a percentage.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] For example, a five nines system would statistically provide 99.999% availability.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Fault-tolerant systems are typically based on the concept of redundancy.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Research into the kinds of tolerances needed for critical systems involves a large amount of interdisciplinary work.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] The more complex the system, the more carefully all possible interactions have to be considered and prepared for.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] All implementations of RAID, redundant array of independent disks, except RAID 0, are examples of a fault-tolerant storage device that uses data redundancy.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] A lockstep fault-tolerant machine uses replicated elements operating in parallel.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] At any time, all the replications of each element should be in the same state.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] The same inputs are provided to each replication, and the same outputs are expected.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] The outputs of the replications are compared using a voting circuit.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] A machine with two replications of each element is termed dual modular redundant (DMR).
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can then only detect a mismatch and recovery relies on other methods.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] A machine with three replications of each element is termed triple modular redundant (TMR).
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can determine which replication is in error when a two-to-one vote is observed.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] In this case, the voting circuit can output the correct result, and discard the erroneous version.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] After this, the internal state of the erroneous replication is assumed to be different from that of the other two, and the voting circuit can switch to a DMR mode.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] This model can be applied to any larger number of replications.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Lockstep fault-tolerant machines are most easily made fully synchronous, with each gate of each replication making the same state transition on the same edge of the clock, and the clocks to the replications being exactly in phase.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] However, it is possible to build lockstep systems without this requirement.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Bringing the replications into synchrony requires making their internal stored states the same.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] They can be started from a fixed initial state, such as the reset state.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, the internal state of one replica can be copied to another replica.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] One variant of DMR is **pair-and-spare**.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Two replicated elements operate in lockstep as a pair, with a voting circuit that detects any mismatch between their operations and outputs a signal indicating that there is an error.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Another pair operates exactly the same way.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] A final circuit selects the output of the pair that does not proclaim that it is in error.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Pair-and-spare requires four replicas rather than the three of TMR, but has been used commercially.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] The approach has performance costs: because the technique rewrites code to insert dynamic checks for address validity, execution time will increase by 80% to 500%.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Recovery shepherding is a lightweight technique to enable software programs to recover from otherwise fatal errors such as null pointer dereference and divide by zero.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Comparing to the failure oblivious computing technique, recovery shepherding works on the compiled program binary directly and does not need to recompile to program.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] It uses the just-in-time binary instrumentation framework Pin.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] It attaches to the application process when an error occurs, repairs the execution, tracks the repair effects as the execution continues, contains the repair effects within the application process, and detaches from the process after all repair effects are flushed from the process state.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] It does not interfere with the normal execution of the program and therefore incurs negligible overhead.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] For 17 of 18 systematically collected real world null-dereference and divide-by-zero errors, a prototype implementation enables the application to continue to execute to provide acceptable output and service to its users on the error-triggering inputs.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] The circuit breaker design pattern is a technique to avoid catastrophic failures in distributed systems.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Redundancy is the provision of functional capabilities that would be unnecessary in a fault-free environment.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] This can consist of backup components that automatically "kick in" if one component fails.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] For example, large cargo trucks can lose a tire without any major consequences.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] They have many tires, and no one tire is critical (with the exception of the front tires, which are used to steer, but generally carry less load, each and in total, than the other four to 16, so are less likely to fail).
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] The idea of incorporating redundancy in order to improve the reliability of a system was pioneered by John von Neumann in the 1950s.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Two kinds of redundancy are possible: space redundancy and time redundancy.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy provides additional components, functions, or data items that are unnecessary for fault-free operation.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy is further classified into hardware, software and information redundancy, depending on the type of redundant resources added to the system.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] In time redundancy the computation or data transmission is repeated and the result is compared to a stored copy of the previous result.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] The current terminology for this kind of testing is referred to as In Service Fault Tolerance Testing or ISFTT for short.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] There is a difference between fault tolerance and systems that rarely have problems.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] For instance, the Western Electric crossbar systems had failure rates of two hours per forty years, and therefore were highly *fault resistant*.
[src:apache-hadoop/fault-tolerance] But when a fault did occur, they stopped operating completely, and therefore were not *fault tolerant*.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS) is a distributed file system designed to run on commodity hardware.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] It has many similarities with existing distributed file systems.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] However, the differences from other distributed file systems are significant.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] HDFS is highly fault-tolerant and is designed to be deployed on low-cost hardware.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] HDFS provides high throughput access to application data and is suitable for applications that have large data sets.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] HDFS relaxes a few POSIX requirements to enable streaming access to file system data.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] HDFS was originally built as infrastructure for the Apache Nutch web search engine project.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] HDFS is part of the Apache Hadoop Core project.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The project URL is http://hadoop.apache.org/.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Hardware failure is the norm rather than the exception.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] An HDFS instance may consist of hundreds or thousands of server machines, each storing part of the file system’s data.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The fact that there are a huge number of components and that each component has a non-trivial probability of failure means that some component of HDFS is always non-functional.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Therefore, detection of faults and quick, automatic recovery from them is a core architectural goal of HDFS.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Applications that run on HDFS need streaming access to their data sets.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] They are not general purpose applications that typically run on general purpose file systems.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] HDFS is designed more for batch processing rather than interactive use by users.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The emphasis is on high throughput of data access rather than low latency of data access.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] POSIX imposes many hard requirements that are not needed for applications that are targeted for HDFS.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] POSIX semantics in a few key areas has been traded to increase data throughput rates.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Applications that run on HDFS have large data sets.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] A typical file in HDFS is gigabytes to terabytes in size.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Thus, HDFS is tuned to support large files.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] It should provide high aggregate data bandwidth and scale to hundreds of nodes in a single cluster.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] It should support tens of millions of files in a single instance.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] HDFS applications need a write-once-read-many access model for files.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] A file once created, written, and closed need not be changed except for appends and truncates.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Appending the content to the end of the files is supported but cannot be updated at arbitrary point.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] This assumption simplifies data coherency issues and enables high throughput data access.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] A MapReduce application or a web crawler application fits perfectly with this model.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] A computation requested by an application is much more efficient if it is executed near the data it operates on.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] This is especially true when the size of the data set is huge.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] This minimizes network congestion and increases the overall throughput of the system.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The assumption is that it is often better to migrate the computation closer to where the data is located rather than moving the data to where the application is running.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] HDFS provides interfaces for applications to move themselves closer to where the data is located.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] HDFS has been designed to be easily portable from one platform to another.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] This facilitates widespread adoption of HDFS as a platform of choice for a large set of applications.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] An HDFS cluster consists of a single NameNode, a master server that manages the file system namespace and regulates access to files by clients.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] In addition, there are a number of DataNodes, usually one per node in the cluster, which manage storage attached to the nodes that they run on.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] HDFS exposes a file system namespace and allows user data to be stored in files.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Internally, a file is split into one or more blocks and these blocks are stored in a set of DataNodes.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The NameNode executes file system namespace operations like opening, closing, and renaming files and directories.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] It also determines the mapping of blocks to DataNodes.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The DataNodes are responsible for serving read and write requests from the file system’s clients.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The DataNodes also perform block creation, deletion, and replication upon instruction from the NameNode.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The NameNode and DataNode are pieces of software designed to run on commodity machines.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] These machines typically run a GNU/Linux operating system (OS).
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] HDFS is built using the Java language; any machine that supports Java can run the NameNode or the DataNode software.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Usage of the highly portable Java language means that HDFS can be deployed on a wide range of machines.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] A typical deployment has a dedicated machine that runs only the NameNode software.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Each of the other machines in the cluster runs one instance of the DataNode software.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The architecture does not preclude running multiple DataNodes on the same machine but in a real deployment that is rarely the case.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The existence of a single NameNode in a cluster greatly simplifies the architecture of the system.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The NameNode is the arbitrator and repository for all HDFS metadata.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The system is designed in such a way that user data never flows through the NameNode.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] HDFS supports a traditional hierarchical file organization.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] A user or an application can create directories and store files inside these directories.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The file system namespace hierarchy is similar to most other existing file systems; one can create and remove files, move a file from one directory to another, or rename a file.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] HDFS supports user quotas and access permissions.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] HDFS does not support hard links or soft links.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] However, the HDFS architecture does not preclude implementing these features.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] While HDFS follows naming convention of the FileSystem, some paths and names (e.g.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] `/.reserved` and `.snapshot` ) are reserved.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Features such as transparent encryption and snapshot use reserved paths.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The NameNode maintains the file system namespace.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Any change to the file system namespace or its properties is recorded by the NameNode.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] An application can specify the number of replicas of a file that should be maintained by HDFS.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The number of copies of a file is called the replication factor of that file.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] This information is stored by the NameNode.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] HDFS is designed to reliably store very large files across machines in a large cluster.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] It stores each file as a sequence of blocks.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The blocks of a file are replicated for fault tolerance.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The block size and replication factor are configurable per file.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] All blocks in a file except the last block are the same size, while users can start a new block without filling out the last block to the configured block size after the support for variable length block was added to append and hsync.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] An application can specify the number of replicas of a file.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The replication factor can be specified at file creation time and can be changed later.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Files in HDFS are write-once (except for appends and truncates) and have strictly one writer at any time.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The NameNode makes all decisions regarding replication of blocks.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] It periodically receives a Heartbeat and a Blockreport from each of the DataNodes in the cluster.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Receipt of a Heartbeat implies that the DataNode is functioning properly.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] A Blockreport contains a list of all blocks on a DataNode.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The placement of replicas is critical to HDFS reliability and performance.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Optimizing replica placement distinguishes HDFS from most other distributed file systems.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] This is a feature that needs lots of tuning and experience.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The purpose of a rack-aware replica placement policy is to improve data reliability, availability, and network bandwidth utilization.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The current implementation for the replica placement policy is a first effort in this direction.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The short-term goals of implementing this policy are to validate it on production systems, learn more about its behavior, and build a foundation to test and research more sophisticated policies.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Large HDFS instances run on a cluster of computers that commonly spread across many racks.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Communication between two nodes in different racks has to go through switches.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] In most cases, network bandwidth between machines in the same rack is greater than network bandwidth between machines in different racks.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The NameNode determines the rack id each DataNode belongs to via the process outlined in Hadoop Rack Awareness.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] A simple but non-optimal policy is to place replicas on unique racks.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] This prevents losing data when an entire rack fails and allows use of bandwidth from multiple racks when reading data.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] This policy evenly distributes replicas in the cluster which makes it easy to balance load on component failure.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] However, this policy increases the cost of writes because a write needs to transfer blocks to multiple racks.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] This policy cuts the inter-rack write traffic which generally improves write performance.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The chance of rack failure is far less than that of node failure; this policy does not impact data reliability and availability guarantees.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] However, it does not reduce the aggregate network bandwidth used when reading data since a block is placed in only two unique racks rather than three.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] With this policy, the replicas of a block do not evenly distribute across the racks.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Two replicas are on different nodes of one rack and the remaining replica is on a node of one of the other racks.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] This policy improves write performance without compromising data reliability or read performance.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] If the replication factor is greater than 3, the placement of the 4th and following replicas are determined randomly while keeping the number of replicas per rack below the upper limit (which is basically `(replicas - 1) / racks + 2`).
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Because the NameNode does not allow DataNodes to have multiple replicas of the same block, maximum number of replicas created is the total number of DataNodes at that time.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] After the support for Storage Types and Storage Policies was added to HDFS, the NameNode takes the policy into account for replica placement in addition to the rack awareness described above.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The NameNode chooses nodes based on rack awareness at first, then checks that the candidate node have storage required by the policy associated with the file.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] If the candidate node does not have the storage type, the NameNode looks for another node.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] If enough nodes to place replicas can not be found in the first path, the NameNode looks for nodes having fallback storage types in the second path.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The current, default replica placement policy described here is a work in progress.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] To minimize global bandwidth consumption and read latency, HDFS tries to satisfy a read request from a replica that is closest to the reader.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] If there exists a replica on the same rack as the reader node, then that replica is preferred to satisfy the read request.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] If HDFS cluster spans multiple data centers, then a replica that is resident in the local data center is preferred over any remote replica.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] If the replication factor is greater than 3, the placement of the 4th and following replicas are determined randomly while keeping the number of replicas per rack below the upper limit (which is basically (replicas - 1) / racks + 2).
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Additional to this HDFS supports 4 different pluggable Block Placement Policies.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Users can choose the policy based on their infrastructre and use case.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] By default HDFS supports BlockPlacementPolicyDefault.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] On startup, the NameNode enters a special state called Safemode.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Replication of data blocks does not occur when the NameNode is in the Safemode state.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The NameNode receives Heartbeat and Blockreport messages from the DataNodes.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] A Blockreport contains the list of data blocks that a DataNode is hosting.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Each block has a specified minimum number of replicas.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] A block is considered safely replicated when the minimum number of replicas of that data block has checked in with the NameNode.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] After a configurable percentage of safely replicated data blocks checks in with the NameNode (plus an additional 30 seconds), the NameNode exits the Safemode state.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] It then determines the list of data blocks (if any) that still have fewer than the specified number of replicas.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The NameNode then replicates these blocks to other DataNodes.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The HDFS namespace is stored by the NameNode.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The NameNode uses a transaction log called the EditLog to persistently record every change that occurs to file system metadata.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] For example, creating a new file in HDFS causes the NameNode to insert a record into the EditLog indicating this.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Similarly, changing the replication factor of a file causes a new record to be inserted into the EditLog.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The NameNode uses a file in its local host OS file system to store the EditLog.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The entire file system namespace, including the mapping of blocks to files and file system properties, is stored in a file called the FsImage.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The FsImage is stored as a file in the NameNode’s local file system too.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The NameNode keeps an image of the entire file system namespace and file Blockmap in memory.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] When the NameNode starts up, or a checkpoint is triggered by a configurable threshold, it reads the FsImage and EditLog from disk, applies all the transactions from the EditLog to the in-memory representation of the FsImage, and flushes out this new version into a new FsImage on disk.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] It can then truncate the old EditLog because its transactions have been applied to the persistent FsImage.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The purpose of a checkpoint is to make sure that HDFS has a consistent view of the file system metadata by taking a snapshot of the file system metadata and saving it to FsImage.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Even though it is efficient to read a FsImage, it is not efficient to make incremental edits directly to a FsImage.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Instead of modifying FsImage for each edit, we persist the edits in the Editlog.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] During the checkpoint the changes from Editlog are applied to the FsImage.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] A checkpoint can be triggered at a given time interval (`dfs.namenode.checkpoint.period`) expressed in seconds, or after a given number of filesystem transactions have accumulated (`dfs.namenode.checkpoint.txns`).
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] If both of these properties are set, the first threshold to be reached triggers a checkpoint.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The DataNode stores HDFS data in files in its local file system.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The DataNode has no knowledge about HDFS files.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] It stores each block of HDFS data in a separate file in its local file system.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The DataNode does not create all files in the same directory.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Instead, it uses a heuristic to determine the optimal number of files per directory and creates subdirectories appropriately.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] It is not optimal to create all local files in the same directory because the local file system might not be able to efficiently support a huge number of files in a single directory.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] When a DataNode starts up, it scans through its local file system, generates a list of all HDFS data blocks that correspond to each of these local files, and sends this report to the NameNode.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] All HDFS communication protocols are layered on top of the TCP/IP protocol.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] A client establishes a connection to a configurable TCP port on the NameNode machine.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] It talks the ClientProtocol with the NameNode.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The DataNodes talk to the NameNode using the DataNode Protocol.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] A Remote Procedure Call (RPC) abstraction wraps both the Client Protocol and the DataNode Protocol.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] By design, the NameNode never initiates any RPCs.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Instead, it only responds to RPC requests issued by DataNodes or clients.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The primary objective of HDFS is to store data reliably even in the presence of failures.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The three common types of failures are NameNode failures, DataNode failures and network partitions.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Each DataNode sends a Heartbeat message to the NameNode periodically.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] A network partition can cause a subset of DataNodes to lose connectivity with the NameNode.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The NameNode detects this condition by the absence of a Heartbeat message.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The NameNode marks DataNodes without recent Heartbeats as dead and does not forward any new IO requests to them.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Any data that was registered to a dead DataNode is not available to HDFS any more.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] DataNode death may cause the replication factor of some blocks to fall below their specified value.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The NameNode constantly tracks which blocks need to be replicated and initiates replication whenever necessary.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The necessity for re-replication may arise due to many reasons: a DataNode may become unavailable, a replica may become corrupted, a hard disk on a DataNode may fail, or the replication factor of a file may be increased.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The time-out to mark DataNodes dead is conservatively long (over 10 minutes by default) in order to avoid replication storm caused by state flapping of DataNodes.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Users can set shorter interval to mark DataNodes as stale and avoid stale nodes on reading and/or writing by configuration for performance sensitive workloads.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The HDFS architecture is compatible with data rebalancing schemes.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] A scheme might automatically move data from one DataNode to another if the free space on a DataNode falls below a certain threshold.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] In the event of a sudden high demand for a particular file, a scheme might dynamically create additional replicas and rebalance other data in the cluster.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] These types of data rebalancing schemes are not yet implemented.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] It is possible that a block of data fetched from a DataNode arrives corrupted.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] This corruption can occur because of faults in a storage device, network faults, or buggy software.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The HDFS client software implements checksum checking on the contents of HDFS files.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] When a client creates an HDFS file, it computes a checksum of each block of the file and stores these checksums in a separate hidden file in the same HDFS namespace.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] When a client retrieves file contents it verifies that the data it received from each DataNode matches the checksum stored in the associated checksum file.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] If not, then the client can opt to retrieve that block from another DataNode that has a replica of that block.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The FsImage and the EditLog are central data structures of HDFS.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] A corruption of these files can cause the HDFS instance to be non-functional.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] For this reason, the NameNode can be configured to support maintaining multiple copies of the FsImage and EditLog.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Any update to either the FsImage or EditLog causes each of the FsImages and EditLogs to get updated synchronously.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] This synchronous updating of multiple copies of the FsImage and EditLog may degrade the rate of namespace transactions per second that a NameNode can support.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] However, this degradation is acceptable because even though HDFS applications are very data intensive in nature, they are not metadata intensive.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] When a NameNode restarts, it selects the latest consistent FsImage and EditLog to use.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Another option to increase resilience against failures is to enable High Availability using multiple NameNodes either with a shared storage on NFS or using a distributed edit log (called Journal).
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Snapshots support storing a copy of data at a particular instant of time.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] One usage of the snapshot feature may be to roll back a corrupted HDFS instance to a previously known good point in time.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] HDFS is designed to support very large files.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Applications that are compatible with HDFS are those that deal with large data sets.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] These applications write their data only once but they read it one or more times and require these reads to be satisfied at streaming speeds.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] HDFS supports write-once-read-many semantics on files.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] A typical block size used by HDFS is 128 MB.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Thus, an HDFS file is chopped up into 128 MB chunks, and if possible, each chunk will reside on a different DataNode.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] When a client is writing data to an HDFS file with a replication factor of three, the NameNode retrieves a list of DataNodes using a replication target choosing algorithm.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] This list contains the DataNodes that will host a replica of that block.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The client then writes to the first DataNode.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The first DataNode starts receiving the data in portions, writes each portion to its local repository and transfers that portion to the second DataNode in the list.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The second DataNode, in turn starts receiving each portion of the data block, writes that portion to its repository and then flushes that portion to the third DataNode.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Finally, the third DataNode writes the data to its local repository.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Thus, a DataNode can be receiving data from the previous one in the pipeline and at the same time forwarding data to the next one in the pipeline.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Thus, the data is pipelined from one DataNode to the next.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] HDFS can be accessed from applications in many different ways.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Natively, HDFS provides a FileSystem Java API for applications to use.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] A C language wrapper for this Java API and REST API is also available.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] In addition, an HTTP browser and can also be used to browse the files of an HDFS instance.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] By using NFS gateway, HDFS can be mounted as part of the client’s local file system.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] HDFS allows user data to be organized in the form of files and directories.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] It provides a commandline interface called FS shell that lets a user interact with the data in HDFS.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The syntax of this command set is similar to other shells (e.g. bash, csh) that users are already familiar with.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] FS shell is targeted for applications that need a scripting language to interact with the stored data.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The DFSAdmin command set is used for administering an HDFS cluster.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] These are commands that are used only by an HDFS administrator.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] A typical HDFS install configures a web server to expose the HDFS namespace through a configurable TCP port.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] This allows a user to navigate the HDFS namespace and view the contents of its files using a web browser.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] If trash configuration is enabled, files removed by FS Shell is not immediately removed from HDFS.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Instead, HDFS moves it to a trash directory (each user has its own trash directory under `/user/<username>/.Trash`).
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The file can be restored quickly as long as it remains in trash.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Most recent deleted files are moved to the current trash directory (`/user/<username>/.Trash/Current`), and in a configurable interval, HDFS creates checkpoints (under `/user/<username>/.Trash/<date>`) for files in current trash directory and deletes old checkpoints when they are expired.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] See expunge command of FS shell about checkpointing of trash.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] After the expiry of its life in trash, the NameNode deletes the file from the HDFS namespace.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The deletion of a file causes the blocks associated with the file to be freed.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Note that there could be an appreciable time delay between the time a file is deleted by a user and the time of the corresponding increase in free space in HDFS.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Following is an example which will show how the files are deleted from HDFS by FS Shell.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The comment below shows that the file has been moved to Trash directory.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] now we are going to remove the file with skipTrash option, which will not send the file to Trash.It will be completely removed from HDFS.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] We can see now that the Trash directory contains only file test1.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] So file test1 goes to Trash and file test2 is deleted permanently.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] When the replication factor of a file is reduced, the NameNode selects excess replicas that can be deleted.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The next Heartbeat transfers this information to the DataNode.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] The DataNode then removes the corresponding blocks and the corresponding free space appears in the cluster.
[src:apache-hadoop/hdfsdesign] Once again, there might be a time delay between the completion of the setReplication API call and the appearance of free space in the cluster.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The model is a specialization of the *split-apply-combine* strategy for data analysis.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] It is inspired by the map and reduce functions commonly used in functional programming, although their purpose in the MapReduce framework is not the same as in their original forms.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] As such, a single-threaded implementation of MapReduce is usually not faster than a traditional (non-MapReduce) implementation; any gains are usually only seen with multi-threaded implementations on multi-processor hardware.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The use of this model is beneficial only when the optimized distributed shuffle operation (which reduces network communication cost) and fault tolerance features of the MapReduce framework come into play.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Optimizing the communication cost is essential to a good MapReduce algorithm.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] MapReduce libraries have been written in many programming languages, with different levels of optimization.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] A popular open-source implementation that has support for distributed shuffles is part of Apache Hadoop.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The name MapReduce originally referred to the proprietary Google technology, but has since become a generic trademark.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] By 2014, Google was no longer using MapReduce as its primary *big data* processing model, and development on Apache Mahout had moved on to more capable and less disk-oriented mechanisms that incorporated full map and reduce capabilities.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Processing can occur on data stored either in a filesystem (unstructured) or in a database (structured).
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] MapReduce can take advantage of the locality of data, processing it near the place it is stored in order to minimize communication overhead.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] **Shuffle:** worker nodes redistribute data based on the output keys (produced by the `map` function), such that all data belonging to one key is located on the same worker node.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] **Reduce:** worker nodes now process each group of output data, per key, in parallel.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] MapReduce allows for the distributed processing of the map and reduction operations.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Maps can be performed in parallel, provided that each mapping operation is independent of the others; in practice, this is limited by the number of independent data sources and/or the number of CPUs near each source.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Similarly, a set of 'reducers' can perform the reduction phase, provided that all outputs of the map operation that share the same key are presented to the same reducer at the same time, or that the reduction function is associative.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The parallelism also offers some possibility of recovering from partial failure of servers or storage during the operation: if one mapper or reducer fails, the work can be rescheduled – assuming the input data are still available.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] **Run the user-provided Map() code** – Map() is run exactly once for each *K1* key, generating output organized by key *K2*.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] **"Shuffle" the Map output to the Reduce processors** – the MapReduce system designates Reduce processors, assigns the *K2* key each processor should work on, and provides that processor with all the Map-generated data associated with that key.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] **Run the user-provided Reduce() code** – Reduce() is run exactly once for each *K2* key produced by the Map step.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] **Produce the final output** – the MapReduce system collects all the Reduce output, and sorts it by *K2* to produce the final outcome.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] These five steps can be logically thought of as running in sequence – each step starts only after the previous step is completed – although in practice they can be interleaved as long as the final result is not affected.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] In many situations, the input data might have already been distributed ("sharded") among many different servers, in which case step 1 could sometimes be greatly simplified by assigning Map servers that would process the locally present input data.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Similarly, step 3 could sometimes be sped up by assigning Reduce processors that are as close as possible to the Map-generated data they need to process.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The *Map* and *Reduce* functions of *MapReduce* are both defined with respect to data structured in (key, value) pairs.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The *Map* function is applied in parallel to every pair (keyed by `k1`) in the input dataset.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] This produces a list of pairs (keyed by `k2`) for each call.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] After that, the MapReduce framework collects all pairs with the same key (`k2`) from all lists and groups them together, creating one group for each key.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Each *Reduce* call typically produces either one key value pair or an empty return, though one call is allowed to return more than one key value pair.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The returns of all calls are collected as the desired result list.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Thus the MapReduce framework transforms a list of (key, value) pairs into another list of (key, value) pairs.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] This behavior is different from the typical functional programming map and reduce combination, which accepts a list of arbitrary values and returns one single value that combines *all* the values returned by map.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] It is necessary but not sufficient to have implementations of the map and reduce abstractions in order to implement MapReduce.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Distributed implementations of MapReduce require a means of connecting the processes performing the Map and Reduce phases.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Other options are possible, such as direct streaming from mappers to reducers, or for the mapping processors to serve up their results to reducers that query them.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Here, each document is split into words, and each word is counted by the *map* function, using the word as the result key.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The framework puts together all the pairs with the same key and feeds them to the same call to *reduce*.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Thus, this function just needs to sum all of its input values to find the total appearances of that word.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] As another example, imagine that for a database of 1.1 billion people, one would like to compute the average number of social contacts a person has according to age.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Note that in the Reduce function, C is the count of people having in total N contacts, so in the Map function it is natural to write C=1, since every output pair is referring to the contacts of one single person.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The MapReduce system would line up the 1100 Map processors, and would provide each with its corresponding 1 million input records.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The Map step would produce 1.1 billion (Y,(N,1)) records, with Y values ranging between, say, 8 and 103.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The MapReduce System would then line up the 96 Reduce processors by performing shuffling operation of the key/value pairs due to the fact that we need average per age, and provide each with its millions of corresponding input records.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The Reduce step would result in the much reduced set of only 96 output records (Y,A), which would be put in the final result file, sorted by Y.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The count info in the record is important if the processing is reduced more than one time.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] If we reduce it with file #3, we lose the count of how many records we've already seen, so we end up with an average of 9.5 contacts for a 10-year-old person ((9+10)/2), which is wrong.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Software framework architecture adheres to open-closed principle where code is effectively divided into unmodifiable *frozen spots* and extensible *hot spots*.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The frozen spot of the MapReduce framework is a large distributed sort.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The *input reader* divides the input into appropriate size 'splits' (in practice, typically, 64 MB to 128 MB) and the framework assigns one split to each *Map* function.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The *input reader* reads data from stable storage (typically, a distributed file system) and generates key/value pairs.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] A common example will read a directory full of text files and return each line as a record.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The *Map* function takes a series of key/value pairs, processes each, and generates zero or more output key/value pairs.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The input and output types of the map can be (and often are) different from each other.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] If the application is doing a word count, the map function would break the line into words and output a key/value pair for each word.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Each output pair would contain the word as the key and the number of instances of that word in the line as the value.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Each *Map* function output is allocated to a particular *reducer* by the application's *partition* function for sharding purposes.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The *partition* function is given the key and the number of reducers and returns the index of the desired *reducer*.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] A typical default is to hash the key and use the hash value modulo the number of *reducers*.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Between the map and reduce stages, the data are *shuffled* (parallel-sorted / exchanged between nodes) in order to move the data from the map node that produced them to the shard in which they will be reduced.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The shuffle can sometimes take longer than the computation time depending on network bandwidth, CPU speeds, data produced and time taken by map and reduce computations.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The input for each *Reduce* is pulled from the machine where the *Map* ran and sorted using the application's *comparison* function.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The framework calls the application's *Reduce* function once for each unique key in the sorted order.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The *Reduce* can iterate through the values that are associated with that key and produce zero or more outputs.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] In the word count example, the *Reduce* function takes the input values, sums them and generates a single output of the word and the final sum.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The *Output Writer* writes the output of the *Reduce* to the stable storage.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Properties of monoids are the basis for ensuring the validity of MapReduce operations.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] In the Algebird package a Scala implementation of Map/Reduce explicitly requires a monoid class type .
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The operations of MapReduce deal with two types: the type *A* of input data being mapped, and the type *B* of output data being reduced.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The *Map* operation takes individual values of type *A* and produces, for each *a:A* a value *b:B*; The *Reduce* operation requires a binary operation • defined on values of type *B*; it consists of folding all available *b:B* to a single value.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] From a basic requirements point of view, any MapReduce operation must involve the ability to arbitrarily regroup data being reduced.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The second property guarantees that, when parallelized over multiple nodes, the nodes that don't have any data to process would have no impact on the result.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] These two properties amount to having a monoid (*B*, •, *e*) on values of type *B* with operation • and with neutral element *e*.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] There's no requirements on the values of type *A*; an arbitrary function *A* → *B* can be used for the *Map* operation.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] This means that we have a catamorphism *A** → (*B*, •, *e*).
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Here *A** denotes a Kleene star, also known as the type of lists over *A*.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The *Shuffle* operation per se is not related to the essence of MapReduce; it's needed to distribute calculations over the cloud.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] It follows from the above that not every binary *Reduce* operation will work in MapReduce.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] MapReduce programs are not guaranteed to be fast.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The main benefit of this programming model is to exploit the optimized shuffle operation of the platform, and only having to write the *Map* and *Reduce* parts of the program.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] In practice, the author of a MapReduce program however has to take the shuffle step into consideration; in particular the partition function and the amount of data written by the *Map* function can have a large impact on the performance and scalability.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Additional modules such as the *Combiner* function can help to reduce the amount of data written to disk, and transmitted over the network.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] MapReduce applications can achieve sub-linear speedups under specific circumstances.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] When designing a MapReduce algorithm, the author needs to choose a good tradeoff between the computation and the communication costs.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Communication cost often dominates the computation cost, and many MapReduce implementations are designed to write all communication to distributed storage for crash recovery.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] In tuning performance of MapReduce, the complexity of mapping, shuffle, sorting (grouping by the key), and reducing has to be taken into account.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The amount of data produced by the mappers is a key parameter that shifts the bulk of the computation cost between mapping and reducing.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Reducing includes sorting (grouping of the keys) which has nonlinear complexity.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Hence, small partition sizes reduce sorting time, but there is a trade-off because having a large number of reducers may be impractical.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The influence of split unit size is marginal (unless chosen particularly badly, say <1MB).
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The gains from some mappers reading load from local disks, on average, is minor.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] For processes that complete quickly, and where the data fits into main memory of a single machine or a small cluster, using a MapReduce framework usually is not effective.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Since these frameworks are designed to recover from the loss of whole nodes during the computation, they write interim results to distributed storage.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] This crash recovery is expensive, and only pays off when the computation involves many computers and a long runtime of the computation.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] A task that completes in seconds can just be restarted in the case of an error, and the likelihood of at least one machine failing grows quickly with the cluster size.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] On such problems, implementations keeping all data in memory and simply restarting a computation on node failures or —when the data is small enough— non-distributed solutions will often be faster than a MapReduce system.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] MapReduce achieves reliability by parceling out a number of operations on the set of data to each node in the network.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Each node is expected to report back periodically with completed work and status updates.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] If a node falls silent for longer than that interval, the master node (similar to the master server in the Google File System) records the node as dead and sends out the node's assigned work to other nodes.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Individual operations use atomic operations for naming file outputs as a check to ensure that there are not parallel conflicting threads running.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] When files are renamed, it is possible to also copy them to another name in addition to the name of the task (allowing for side-effects).
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The reduce operations operate much the same way.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Because of their inferior properties with regard to parallel operations, the master node attempts to schedule reduce operations on the same node, or in the same rack as the node holding the data being operated on.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] This property is desirable as it conserves bandwidth across the backbone network of the datacenter.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Implementations are not necessarily highly reliable.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] For example, in older versions of Hadoop the *NameNode* was a single point of failure for the distributed filesystem.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Moreover, the MapReduce model has been adapted to several computing environments like multi-core and many-core systems, desktop grids, multi-cluster, volunteer computing environments, dynamic cloud environments, mobile environments, and high-performance computing environments.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] At Google, MapReduce was used to completely regenerate Google's index of the World Wide Web.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] It replaced the old *ad hoc* programs that updated the index and ran the various analyses.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Development at Google has since moved on to technologies such as Percolator, FlumeJava and MillWheel that offer streaming operation and updates instead of batch processing, to allow integrating "live" search results without rebuilding the complete index.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] MapReduce's stable inputs and outputs are usually stored in a distributed file system.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The transient data are usually stored on local disk and fetched remotely by the reducers.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] David DeWitt and Michael Stonebraker, computer scientists specializing in parallel databases and shared-nothing architectures, have been critical of the breadth of problems that MapReduce can be used for.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] They called its interface too low-level and questioned whether it really represents the paradigm shift its proponents have claimed it is.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] They challenged the MapReduce proponents' claims of novelty, citing Teradata as an example of prior art that has existed for over two decades.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Greg Jorgensen wrote an article rejecting these views.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] Jorgensen asserts that DeWitt and Stonebraker's entire analysis is groundless as MapReduce was never designed nor intended to be used as a database.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] DeWitt and Stonebraker have subsequently published a detailed benchmark study in 2009 comparing performance of Hadoop's MapReduce and RDBMS approaches on several specific problems.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] They concluded that relational databases offer real advantages for many kinds of data use, especially on complex processing or where the data is used across an enterprise, but that MapReduce may be easier for users to adopt for simple or one-time processing tasks.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The MapReduce programming paradigm was also described in Danny Hillis's 1985 thesis intended for use on the Connection Machine, where it was called "xapping/reduction" and relied upon that machine's special hardware to accelerate both map and reduce.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The dialect ultimately used for the Connection Machine, the 1986 StarLisp, had parallel `*map` and `reduce!!`, which in turn was based on the 1984 Common Lisp, which had non-parallel `map` and `reduce` built in.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The tree-like approach that the Connection Machine's hypercube architecture uses to execute `reduce` in $O(\log n)$ time is effectively the same as the approach referred to within the Google paper as prior work.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] In 2010 Google was granted what is described as a patent on MapReduce.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The patent, filed in 2004, may cover use of MapReduce by open source software such as Hadoop, CouchDB, and others.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] In *Ars Technica*, an editor acknowledged Google's role in popularizing the MapReduce concept, but questioned whether the patent was valid or novel.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] In 2013, as part of its "Open Patent Non-Assertion (OPN) Pledge", Google pledged to only use the patent defensively.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] The patent is expected to expire on 23 December 2026.
[src:apache-hadoop/mapreduce] MapReduce tasks must be written as acyclic dataflow programs, i.e. a stateless mapper followed by a stateless reducer, that are executed by a batch job scheduler.
